Preheat your oven to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm wide wedges (no need
to peel). Pop the wedges onto a #baking tray{} and drizzle with @oil{}. Season with
@salt{} and @pepper{} and toss to coat. Roast on the top shelf of your oven until
soft and golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

Meanwhile, trim the @carrot{1}(trimmed and coarsely grated) and coarsely grate (no
need to peel). Trim the root from the @baby gem lettuce{1} then halve lengthways.
Thinly slice widthways. Trim the @spring onion{1} then slice thinly. Put the
lettuce, carrot and spring onion into a #mixing bowl{} and add a drizzle of
@olive oil{} and a pinch of @salt{} and @pepper{}. Mix well to combine.

Heat a drizzle of @vegetable oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.
Sprinkle the @North Indian style spice mix{1%tbsp} over the @chicken breast{260%g}(diced)
along with a pinch of salt and pepper. Use your hands to rub the flavours over
the pieces of chicken.

> IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat.

Once hot, add the chicken to the pan. Fry until golden and cooked through,
turning frequently, ~{12-15%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Once the chicken is cooked, transfer to a #bowl{} and cover with #foil{} to keep
warm. Return the pan to a medium heat and add the @water{100%ml}, @peanut butter{1%tbsp},
@sugar{1%tsp} and a pinch of salt and pepper to the pan. Stir continuously until
the peanut butter has melted and the sauce has thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Remove
from the heat.

Gently stir the chicken (and any resting juices) into the sauce to nicely coat all
of the pieces. Return the pan to a low heat until the chicken is piping hot,
~{2-3%minutes}.

To assemble, lay out the @super soft tortillas with whole wheat{4}. Divide the
salad between them then top with the satay chicken. Fold over one end to encase
the base of the filling, then roll up like a fajita. Serve with the wedges on the
side. Enjoy!